{"title_page": "List of Skittles products", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2012}}\n'''[[Skittles (confectionery)|Skittles]]''' candy products, produced by [[kellogs ]], come in a wide variety. Most of the varieties are available only in particular regions of the world. The oldest Skittles product is Original Fruit Skittles, which was originally released in Europe in 1974, and was launched in the United States in 1979.<ref name=\"Wrigley\">{{cite web | title=Skittles | url=http://www.wrigley.com/global/brands/skittles.aspx | work=Wrigley Company | publisher=Wrigley Company | date= | accessdate=2010-07-04 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027112505/http://www.wrigley.com/global/brands/skittles.aspx | archive-date=2012-10-27 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The most recent flavor, Sweet Heat, was released in 2018. Earlier Skittles products tended to focus on fruit flavors, more recent products have branched out to include flavors such as chocolate, bubble gum, popcorn, mint, and sours. Skittles products also come in a wide variety of colors, although different Skittles products often use the same colors for sweets with different flavors. For example, the color yellow is associated with lemon flavor in Original Fruit Skittles and as banana berry in Tropical Skittles.\n\nThe original Skittles in the United States were orange, lemon, lime, grape and strawberry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrigley.com/global/brands/skittles.aspx |title=Skittles &#124; Skittles Flavors &#124; Skittles Candy |publisher=Wrigley.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027112505/http://www.wrigley.com/global/brands/skittles.aspx |archive-date=2012-10-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the United States Skittles lime was changed to green apple.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/todayilearned/comments/1arqcv/til_that_the_green_skittle_is_now_apple_flavored/ |title=TIL that the green skittle apple : todayilearned |publisher=Reddit.com |date=2013-03-22 |accessdate=2017-11-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodbeast.com/news/skittles-swaps-green-apple-flavor-with-lime-changes-original-rainbow/ |title=Skittles Swaps Green Apple Flavor with Lime, Changes 'Original' Rainbow |publisher=Foodbeast.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-07}}</ref> A \"Long Lost Lime\" variation of Skittles has been released in summer 2017 and 2018, bringing the lime flavor back to the original mix of Skittles for a limited time only.\n\n==List==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Name'''\n| '''Colors and flavors'''\n| '''Notes'''\n| '''Year'''\n|-\n| Original Skittles\n|\n* [[Blackcurrant]], [[Kiwifruit]], or [[Grape]] (purple), ''see notes''\n* [[Lemon]] (yellow)\n* [[Apple|Green Apple]] or [[Lime (fruit)|Lime]] (green), ''see notes''\n* [[Orange (fruit)|Orange]] (orange)\n* [[Strawberry]] (red)\n* [[Cherry cola]] (blue)   ''Included in a limited edition in the UK.''\n| In [[Ireland]], the [[United Kingdom]], Sweden and [[Germany]] purple Skittles are [[blackcurrant]]. <br />\nIn [[Taiwan]], [[South Korea]], [[China]], [[Australia]], and, as of 2013, the [[United States of America]] Lime is replaced with Green Apple flavor.<br /> Lime was moved to the \"Darkside\" flavor in 2013 (but called \"Midnight Lime\" in said product Darkside Skittles).\nGreen Apple also replaced Lime in the [[United States of America]] for a brief time in April 2001, as part of a promotion.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Great Skittle Debate |publisher=February-7.com |author=JPS |url=http://www.february-7.com/index.asp?cat=Personal |accessdate=2008-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030219095950/http://www.february-7.com/index.asp?cat=Personal |archivedate=February 19, 2003 }}</ref> In 2013, this change was made permanent.\n| 1974<ref name=\"Wrigley\" />\n|-\n| Tropical (Rainforest)\n|\n* [[Banana]] [[Berry]] (yellow)\n* [[Kiwifruit|Kiwi]] [[Lime (fruit)|Lime]] (green)\n* [[Mango]] [[Tangelo]] (orange)\n* [[Pineapple]] [[Passion fruit]] (blue)\n* [[Strawberry]] [[Carambola|Starfruit]] (pink)\n|Tropical Skittles typically have two flavors in one skittle.<ref name=\"Wrigley\" /><!-- The product is sold in either light blue bags or boxes; originally, they came in red-orange bags or boxes. importance? -->\n| 1989<ref name=\"Wrigley\" />\n|-\n| Wild Berry \n|\n* [[Berry]] [[Punch (drink)|Punch]] (violet)\n* [[Melon]] [[Berry]] (green)\n* [[Raspberry]] (blue)\n* [[Strawberry]] (pink)\n* [[Cherry|Wild Cherry]] (red)\n|Was launched in [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] in 2012 and in the UK in 2014. A variant with fizzy powder existed in 2010-2011 (known as Fizzl'd Fruits), but some of the colors were changed.\n| 1989<ref name=\"Wrigley\" />\n|-\n| Tart-N-Tangy\n| Flavors were those that represent the sour Skittles that were released after these were discontinued with slight differences to the flavors. Specifics on the flavors are sketchy.\n| Discontinued in 1992. Was later replaced by Sour Skittles in the bright green package. \n| 1989\n|-\n| Crazy Cores\n|(shell color, core)\n* [[Blue raspberry flavor|Blue Raspberry]] [[Lemon]] (B, Y)\n* [[Cherry]] [[Lemonade]] (R, Y)\n* [[Mango]] [[Peach]] (O, R)\n* [[Melon]] [[Berry]] (P, G)\n* [[Strawberry]] [[Watermelon]] (G, P)\n|Sold in bulk stores in the U.S. (e.g., [[Sam's Club]])<br> Introduced in the [[United Kingdom]] in 2011. Withdrawn from the UK in 2013, replaced by Confused Skittles\n| 2008<ref name=\"Mars press release\">[http://www.prnewswire.com/mnr/mars/35287/ Mars Press Release]</ref>/2011 (UK) \n|-\n| Skittles Confused\n| The flavors were meant to be Fruit Skittles with the colors and flavors mixed up, showing the answers on the back.\n| Skittles with mixed up flavors and colors. Sold for a short time in the [[United Kingdom]] in 2008. They came in purple bags with a large question mark.\n| 2008\n|-\n\n| Confused?\n| Similar to an incarnation previously sold in the [[United Kingdom